A total of 95 bacterial and 94 fungal strains were identified. These strains were well-distributed along soil depths and pollutant (Supplementary Tables 
 S2, 
 S3). The taxonomical identification of bacteria confirmed the selection of specific bacterial communities following the addition of different hydrocarbons, indicating a high specialization of bacterial taxa involved in their degradation. 
 Proteobacteria, Firmicutes, and 
 Sphingobacteria were the prevailing bacterial phyla: all these phyla comprised several phylogenetic groups involved in the aerobic degradation of hydrocarbons (
 Vinas et al., 2005; 
 Head et al., 2006; 
 Yang et al., 2012; 
 Yergeau et al., 2012). 
 Proteobacteria was also found as the most abundant phylum distributed in an environment contaminated with petroleum muck and in activated biomass from a petrochemical industry wastewater sample (
 Joshi et al., 2014; 
 Yadav et al., 2015). This phylum is divided into five major classes, all with oil-degrading genera (
 Gao et al., 2014). On the whole, isolated bacteria where ascribed mainly to genera belonging to Gamma-proteobacteria class, whose dominance within the enriched microcosms can be expected since it comprises many of the hydrocarbonoclastic bacteria responsible for the first steps of hydrocarbons degradation (
 Head et al., 2006; 
 Yakimov et al., 2007; 
 Barbato et al., 2016).
